recalls.Summary: PORSCHE IS RECALLING CERTAIN MODEL YEAR 2011 911 SPEEDSTER AND 911 GTS RS 4.0; AND MODEL YEAR 2012 BOXSTER (INCLUDING S AND SPYDER); CAYMAN (INCLUDING S AND R); 911 CARRERA (INCLUDING S, GTS, 4, 4S, AND 4 GTS); 911 TARGA 4 AND TARGA 4S; AND 911 TURBO AND TURBO S MODELS MANUFACTURED FROM MAY 31, 2011, THROUGH JUNE 10, 2011.  THERE IS A POSSIBILITY THAT THE MOUNTING HOLES IN THE SEAT BELT ANCHOR PLATES FITTED TO THE VEHICLE ARE TOO SMALL.  IF THE HOLE DIAMETER IS TOO SMALL, THE ANCHOR PLATE MAY NOT BE ABLE TO ROTATE ABOUT THE FASTENING BOLT AS DESIGNED.
recalls.Consequence: SHOULD THIS OCCUR, THE SEAT BELT MAY NOT BE ROUTED OPTIMALLY AROUND THE OCCUPANT, OR MAY POTENTIALLY LOOSEN AT SOME POINT IN THE FUTURE INCREASING THE RISK OF INJURY DURING A CRASH.
recalls.Remedy: PORSCHE WILL NOTIFY OWNERS, AND DEALERS WILL INSPECT THE SEAT BELT ANCHORS AND, IF NECESSARY, REPLACE THE SEAT BELT.  THE REPAIRS WILL BE PERFORMED FREE OF CHARGE.  THE SAFETY RECALL BEGAN ON SEPTEMBER 2, 2011.  OWNERS MAY CONTACT PORSCHE AT 1-800-767-7243.
recalls.Notes: PORSCHE'S SAFETY RECALL NUMBER IS AB02. OWNERS MAY ALSO CONTACT THE NATIONAL HIGHWAY TRAFFIC SAFETY ADMINISTRATION'S VEHICLE SAFETY HOTLINE AT 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), OR GO TO HTTP://WWW.SAFERCAR.GOV .

issues.title: IMS Bearing Failure
issues.description: Intermediate Shaft (IMS) bearing failure can cause catastrophic engine damage. The bearing supports the intermediate shaft that drives the camshafts, and failure results in complete engine destruction.
issues.fix_description: Complete engine rebuild or replacement required. IMS bearing upgrade during engine rebuild.
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with quality oil, consider preventive IMS bearing upgrade

issues.title: RMS (Rear Main Seal) Oil Leak
issues.description: The rear main seal commonly fails causing oil leaks at the back of the engine. This is a common issue requiring engine removal for repair.
issues.fix_description: Engine removal required to replace rear main seal and related gaskets
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid overheating engine

issues.title: Water Pump Failure
issues.description: Water pump failure is common and can lead to engine overheating. The plastic impeller can crack or the bearing can fail.
issues.fix_description: Replace water pump, thermostat, and coolant hoses during repair
issues.prevention: Regular coolant flushes, monitor coolant levels

issues.title: Convertible Top Motor Failure
issues.description: The convertible top motor commonly fails, preventing the top from operating properly. The motor overheats or the pump fails.
issues.fix_description: Replace convertible top motor and hydraulic pump assembly
issues.prevention: Regular operation of top, avoid forcing operation when stuck

issues.title: PDK Transmission Clutch Pack Failure
issues.description: PDK dual-clutch transmission clutch packs can fail, causing harsh shifting, loss of gears, or complete transmission failure.
issues.fix_description: PDK transmission rebuild or replacement with updated clutch packs
issues.prevention: Regular PDK service intervals, avoid aggressive launching

issues.title: AOS (Air Oil Separator) Failure
issues.description: The Air Oil Separator fails causing excessive oil consumption and smoking from the exhaust. Common failure point in Porsche engines.
issues.fix_description: Replace AOS unit and related vacuum lines
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid overfilling oil

issues.title: Coolant Tank Cracking
issues.description: The plastic coolant expansion tank commonly develops cracks, leading to coolant loss and potential overheating.
issues.fix_description: Replace coolant expansion tank and cap
issues.prevention: Regular coolant system inspection, avoid overheating

issues.title: Ignition Coil Failure
issues.description: Ignition coils fail causing misfires and rough running. Carbon buildup on direct injection engines accelerates coil failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed ignition coils and spark plugs
issues.prevention: Regular spark plug replacement, quality fuel usage

issues.title: Carbon Buildup on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection engines suffer from carbon buildup on intake valves, reducing performance and fuel economy.
issues.fix_description: Walnut blasting or chemical cleaning of intake valves
issues.prevention: Regular highway driving, quality fuel, occasional Italian tune-up

issues.title: Door Handle Mechanism Failure
issues.description: Interior door handle mechanisms commonly break, making it difficult to exit the vehicle from inside.
issues.fix_description: Replace door handle mechanism and cables
issues.prevention: Gentle operation of door handles, regular lubrication

issues.title: PASM Suspension Strut Failure
issues.description: Porsche Active Suspension Management (PASM) struts can fail, causing poor ride quality and suspension warning lights.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed PASM strut(s) with OEM or aftermarket units
issues.prevention: Avoid harsh impacts, regular suspension inspection

editorial.tagline: Pure flat-six symphony in perfect roadster form
editorial.hero_blurb: The 981 Boxster S represents Porsche's roadster at its zenith - a perfectly balanced mid-engine masterpiece that delivers intoxicating naturally aspirated power. This is the last of the pure, unfiltered Boxster experience before turbocharging changed everything.
editorial.essence: The 981 Boxster S captures everything magical about Porsche's engineering philosophy in one sublime package. Its 3.4-liter flat-six sings with an urgency that modern turbo engines simply can't match, while the mid-engine layout provides balance that borders on telepathic.
editorial.heritage: Born from Porsche's racing DNA and the iconic 550 Spyder lineage, the Boxster emerged in 1996 to save Porsche from financial ruin. The 981 generation, launched in 2012, refined two decades of mid-engine expertise into the most accomplished Boxster ever built.
editorial.design_philosophy: Porsche's designers sought to create the purest expression of driving pleasure - every line serves aerodynamics and function, every surface optimized for performance. The 981's proportions are mathematically perfect, with short overhangs and a cab-forward stance that screams purpose.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not a direct racing derivative, the Boxster shares fundamental DNA with Porsche's Le Mans-winning prototypes. The mid-engine layout and flat-six configuration echo the 917 and RS Spyder racers that dominated endurance racing.
editorial.engine_character: The 3.4L flat-six is automotive poetry in motion - smooth as silk below 4,000 RPM, then transforming into a snarling beast that pulls relentlessly to 7,800 RPM. Every throttle input is met with immediate, linear response that builds to an intoxicating crescendo.
editorial.transmission_feel: The six-speed manual shifts with mechanical precision that borders on surgical - short throws, perfect gates, and a clutch with just enough weight to feel serious. The optional PDK dual-clutch is lightning-quick but lacks the manual's emotional connection.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Mid-engine perfection delivers balanced handling that flatters drivers while rewarding skill. The chassis rotates naturally through corners with neutral stability that builds confidence, while the low center of gravity keeps everything planted and predictable.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulic power steering provides genuine road feel that's increasingly rare - every pebble, every camber change transmitted through your fingertips. Weighting is perfectly judged, requiring effort at parking speeds but lightening naturally as speeds rise.
editorial.brake_confidence: Porsche's brakes inspire absolute confidence with immediate bite, perfect modulation, and fade-free performance. The pedal feel is firm and consistent, allowing precise threshold braking whether on mountain roads or track days.
editorial.sound_signature: The flat-six's symphony begins as a cultured rumble at idle, building through a hollow, metallic growl in the mid-range before erupting into a spine-tingling wail above 6,000 RPM. It's a sound that stirs the soul and announces your presence with authority.
editorial.ideal_owner: Weekend warriors who prioritize driving purity over comfort, enthusiasts who understand that the journey matters more than the destination, and purists who want the last great naturally aspirated Porsche experience.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Daily commuters needing practicality, owners seeking luxury amenities over driving dynamics, or those who prioritize straight-line speed over handling balance and engine character.
editorial.buyers_summary: The 981 Boxster S represents the end of an era - the last naturally aspirated flat-six Boxster with hydraulic steering and pure driving dynamics. Values are climbing as enthusiasts recognize this as Porsche's final analog sports car, making it both an exceptional driver and smart investment.

expertReviews.title: 2014 Porsche 981 Boxster S Review - Best Used Sports Car ...
pros: Excellent build quality and interior design
Amazing naturally aspirated flat-6 engine sound
Precise handling with X73 sport suspension

expertReviews.verdict: The 981 Boxster S represents exceptional value as a driver's car under $50,000. With its naturally aspirated 3.4L flat-6 making 315 HP, precise handling, and excellent build quality, it offers a compelling alternative to modern hot hatches at similar prices. The reviewer considers it potentially the best streetable driver's car under $50,000, praising its refinement over the previous 987 generation while noting minor criticisms about steering feedback and transmission gearing.

pros: Very reliable with minimal issues over 18 months
Low basic maintenance costs ($1400 over 17 months)
Beautiful sound with sports exhaust
Good dealer support from Porsche Melbourne
Significant savings possible using independent specialists
cons: Headlights prone to crazing and yellowing
PDK transmission expensive to replace if fails ($25,000)
Dealer parts and service costs very high

expertReviews.verdict: After 18 months and 15,000km, the 981 Boxster has proven very reliable with only minor issues like battery, alarm module, and HVAC blower needing attention. Owner achieved significant cost savings ($7,650 total) by using independent specialists rather than dealers. The car delivers excellent driving enjoyment but requires careful budgeting for maintenance due to high Porsche dealer costs.

expertReviews.verdict: The 981 Boxster S is described as an 'absolute dream' offering everything you want from a Porsche experience at good value. With 315 BHP from the 3.4L flat-6, excellent handling, and practical storage, it's positioned as the ideal choice for those wanting a true Porsche experience without significant depreciation. The reviewer emphasizes this is the last naturally aspirated Boxster, making it increasingly desirable.

expertReviews.verdict: The 981 Boxster (2012-2016) is an attractive sports car that resembles the Carrera GT, but buyers should be prepared for potentially expensive maintenance issues. Key areas of concern include oil and coolant leaks, PDK transmission problems, costly suspension and brake repairs, AC system issues, and interior leather peeling. A pre-purchase inspection is highly recommended due to the numerous potential expensive repairs.

The reviewer emphasizes the excellent PDK transmission, fantastic exhaust note, and overall driving experience. Despite some minor drawbacks like traction issues and soft top noise, it's praised as a great value mid-engine sports car with Porsche reliability.

expertReviews.title: Comparing 3 generations of Porsche Boxster! 987.2 - 981 - 718 Full Review & Why They're All Great!
pros: All three generations are fantastic cars in their own right
Very practical with front and rear boots
Properly designed for open-top driving with minimal buffeting
987 Gen 2 has hydraulic steering with more feedback
981 and 718 have remote hood operation and folding mirrors
718 includes CarPlay connectivity
cons: 987 Gen 2 requires key in ignition to operate hood
981 and 987 Gen 2 lack CarPlay without modifications
718 uses flat-four engine instead of flat-six
Heated seats weren't standard in UK market
expertReviews.verdict: All three Boxster generations offer unique advantages for different use cases. The 987.2 represents the pinnacle of the previous generation with hydraulic steering and more direct feedback. The 981 brings modern conveniences like remote hood operation and improved interior space. The 718 adds CarPlay and updated styling but switches to a flat-four engine. Each excels in its own way depending on buyer priorities.
